title: Advance Senior SIGINT Analystt
description: 2011-2013 Advance Collection Team, U.S Army 7th Special Forces Group (A), EGLIN AFB, FL Served as a Senior Signals Intelligence/Electronic Warfare (SIGINT/EW) Cryptologic Linguist and collection equipment operator in the Technical Control and Analysis Element (TCAE) for the 7th Special Forces Group (Airborne) operating in the CENTCOM and SOUTHCOM Areas of Operations; Assists with technical, analytical and linguistic support for 7th Special Forces Group (Airborne) primary areas of operations. - Provided numerous training with peers to ensure they were trained proficiently in tactical ground equipment; UHF/HF/VHF/Wolfhound System/PRD-13 System/DRT1500 box. - Trained with TICOM Geometrics on GEONET software while still in its testing phase and development. - Trained and became qualified on Counter Electronic Warfare Systems during a three week Electronic Warfare Maintainer course.

summary: Active Top Secret/ SCI clearance with HCS/Gamma Provided Through Single Scope Background Investigation (SSBI). I have completed 8 years SIGINT analyst performance in different Areas of Operations. Skilled Intelligence Analyst with Tactical/Strategic organizational, analytical, and training abilities. Provided SIGINT support to Coalition Force elements through 24-hour watch operations. Utilized numerous IC databases and tipping tools to yield a number of reports daily. Experience in OEF extends to; Low Level Voice Interception (LLVI), Signal Terminal Guidance (STG), numerous program and various SIGINT databases search engines and disciplines. Task Force 3-10 Geospatial analysis while assisting the Tactical Screening Facility, ISR support and Air coordinations, Task-Force 3-10 target development. SIGINT analysis stateside as well as leading elements while providing (STG) SIGINT terminal guidance/VHF ground guidance to overseas in a high stress environment. My first deployment, as a SIGINT Analyst, I was the training NCOIC for the foreign soldiers, late comers to the deployment and anyone who needed assistance fixing equipment, configuring databases/or tools, as well as report- writing / Mission tasking / de-tasking priorities, while supporting air assets during combat operations. I was awarded the Army Joint Service Commendation Medal for my work as a Senior SIGINT Analyst, specifically, for providing accurate information during Combat Operations and preventing attacks to Forces. Completed two rotations to Afghanistan (OEF) as a Senior-Level Ground SIGINT Analyst Operator, and Geospatial Analyst for target development in 2009 and 2010. Additionally, I participated in numerous Objectives providing SIGINT/EW support to Task-Force Commander capturing and neutralizing many OBJs while developing new target packages.

title: Senior SIGINT Analyst (Linguist)
company: Senior Cryptologic Linguist, 75th Ranger Regiment, Ft Benning, GA
description: 2009-2011 Senior Cryptologic Linguist, 75th Ranger Regiment, Ft Benning, GA Senior Cryptologic SIGINT Linguist for a globally deployable tactical Operational SIGINT Team (OST) which conducts Signals Intelligence (SIGINT) and Electronic Warfare (EW) operations in support of the 75th Ranger Regiment Special Troops Battalion and the three Ranger Line Battalions; responsible for exploitation and analysis of communication devices; which conducts SIGINT/EW and radio reconnaissance operations in denied, hostile, and politically sensitive areas; responsible for all linguistic duties for languages in Central and South America; responsible for operational training for the CENTCOM areas of Operations. - Received Army impact award for numerous Tactical combat Operation. - Produced numerous SIGINT reports in response to Request for information from Task Force personnel resulting in the detainment of numerous High Value Targets. - Led SIGINT Team in numerous tactical Objectives who... - Worked as the Geospatial SIGINT Analyst Exploitation NCOIC for a Tactical Screening Facility; CELLEX, DOCEX section. - Conducted Task Force SIGINT daily briefings, Analysis, Target Development, Tactical equipment training, and Mission Support during tactical deployment during Operation Enduring Freedom (OEF).

title: Senior SIGINT Analyst (Linguist)
company: Senior SINGT Analyst, 314st Military Intelligence NSA/CSS Texas, Lackland AFB, TX
description: 2006-2009 Senior SINGT Analyst, 314st Military Intelligence NSA/CSS Texas, Lackland AFB, TX Analyst Leader responsible for the accountability, training and professional development of an eight member Analyst Team; Senior SIGINT Analyst responsible for the daily processing of numerous time sensitive transmission in support of national-level priorities in the Western Hemisphere; employs expert technical knowledge in preparing target packages; supports operations in support of Force Protection Operations; lead trainer and target developer for different target set; provides direct input for operational and strategic planning, programming, and recommendations for optimal production within areas of operations. - Trained joint service and civilian linguists in Special Intelligence Processing Applications; resulted in a weekly production increase of over 30%. - Exceeded NSA/CSS mission standard of 80% by scoring 98% on mission certification test.

summary: Active Top Secret/ SCI clearance with HCS/Gamma Provided Through Single Scope Background Investigation (SSBI). I have completed 8 years SIGINT analyst performance in different Areas of Operations. Skilled Intelligence Analyst with Tactical/Strategic organizational, analytical, and training abilities. Provided SIGINT support to Coalition Force elements through 24-hour watch operations. Utilized numerous IC databases and tipping tools to yield a number of reports daily. Experience in OEF extends to; Low Level Voice Interception (LLVI), Signal Terminal Guidance (STG), numerous program and various SIGINT databases search engines and disciplines. Task Force 3-10 Geospatial analysis while assisting the Tactical Screening Facility, ISR support and Air coordinations, Task-Force 3-10 target development. SIGINT analysis stateside as well as leading elements while providing (STG) SIGINT terminal guidance/VHF ground guidance to overseas in a high stress environment. My first deployment, as a SIGINT Analyst, I was the training NCOIC for the foreign soldiers, late comers to the deployment and anyone who needed assistance fixing equipment, configuring databases/or tools, as well as report- writing / Mission tasking / de-tasking priorities, while supporting air assets during combat operations. I was awarded the Army Joint Service Commendation Medal for my work as a Senior SIGINT Analyst, specifically, for providing accurate information during Combat Operations and preventing attacks to Forces. Completed two rotations to Afghanistan (OEF) as a Senior-Level Ground SIGINT Analyst Operator, and Geospatial Analyst for target development in 2009 and 2010. Additionally, I participated in numerous Objectives providing SIGINT/EW support to Task-Force Commander capturing and neutralizing many OBJs while developing new target packages.

summary: - Squadron Superintendent responsible for all facets of Formal Training Unit operations, responsible for recruiting and staffing for 4 specialty careers within the organization. - Senior intelligence professional with airborne experience in RIVET JOINT, COMPASS CALL and SILENT SHIELD, ground experience with the Afghanistan Remote Operations Cryptologic Center (AROCC) and leadership duties with Project LIBERTY - Heavy focus on education and training as a Command Language Program Manager, RIVET JOINT instructor and evaluator, SILENT SHIELD Cryptologic Skills Program Manager, COMPASS CALL instructor, ACC course manager, Formal Training Unit Superintendent, Defense Language Institute Military Language Instructor and Superintendent of Language Operations - Cryptologic Language Analyst (SIGINT) w/19+ years of experience in training, administrative support, data base creation & management, scheduling, building and presenting intelligence briefings, overall computer application and maintenance proficiency, maintaining operations budgets, developing, coordinating and implementing operational plans - Tactical and strategic level experience in deployed operations as a leader, operator and mission planner during fourteen deployments – 7 x OSW, 2 x ONW, 2 x OIF, 2 x OEF, 1 x OND

title: Operations Superintendent
description: - Executed $240K annual operations budget and $8.9M flying hour program - Ensured combat readiness of 156 members, maintained 10th consecutive year of combat ops - Revamped training management toolkit, reduced backlog by 60% in less than 2 months - Id’d job mismatch, realigned resources, boosted manning 45%, saved $250K in training costs - Headed NCA tasking support, organized manpower/schedule to provide 40% increased support - Directed automated data processing equipment inventory, proper disposition returned $100K - Key advisor on topics including enlisted force career progression and professional development - Responsible for placement, retention and job diversification within the organization of assigned personnel - Advises commander on manning, budget, and trng requirements at squadron, group & wing levels - SME for Farsi and Dari global and cryptologic language training programs, researched, identified and developed language training materials for unclassified and classified courses aligned with NSA/CSS language training requirements, senior mentor for 50 linguists

title: Instructional Design Consultant
company: Language, Science and Technology Directorate, Curriculum Development Division
description: - Led the Persian-Farsi School contingent while on assignment to the Curriculum Development Division, coordinated with deans, department chairs, curriculum developers, editors and production coordinators on the first new Persian-Farsi Basic Course curriculum in over 30 years. - Incorporated Merrill, Kolb and Bloom’s principles during the instructional design process, incorporated direct, explicit grammar instruction and tasked based instruction, promoted an eclectic approach to instructional design that promoted maximum creativity, placed special emphasis on personalized and creative activities that teachers can adapt according to students’ different learning styles, developed a degree of automaticity during the achievement stage of learning via repetition, substitution, transformation & expansion – critical to proficiency growth - Developed materials promoting development in both general proficiency and the Performance Final Learning Objectives (FLOs) which focused on Military and Security, Economic and Politics, Science and Technology, Culture and Society and Geography – Physical, Political and Economic. Also incorporated ancillary FLOs which include dictionary use, manner or tenor, colloquial usage, text processing and transliteration according to customer requirements - Developed lesson evaluations in the form of student self-assessments and unit tests, piloted materials, gathered and analyzed data and developed final revision for delivery to end users - During curricula production, involved the users of the products (faculty and students) during various phases of development and production, incorporated interested parties during the initial development, the design of scope and sequence and the design and field testing of the course components including lessons, homework, quizzes, unit test, etc.

title: Superintendent, Language Operations
company: 314th Training Squadron, Defense Language Institute, Presidio of Monterey, CA
description: - Chief Military Language Instructor, aided the Dean of the Persian-Farsi School, managed 220+ staff and faculty and 440+ joint-service & coalition students, improved graduation rates 23% - Led 23 AF MLIs as Superintendent of Language Operations, provided instruction in 9 languages at 4 schoolhouses to 3K+ joint-service & coalition students, improved graduation rate by 15% - Represented the Defense Language Institute at the Cryptologic Training Advisory Group, streamlined Farsi course by 15% and accelerated support to overseas contingency operations. - Developed the Persian-Farsi School Mentoring Program, identified and secured mentoring for 63 struggling students, directed 53 tutors in the delivery of 893 academic instruction hours - Managed student load 520% higher than NSA standard, delivered 2340 hours of target language instruction, integrated NSA Final Learning Objectives w/focus on transcription & gisting - Utilized DLI – ICC principles, instructed 520+ hours annually, focused on translation, grammar, listening, reading, speaking and writing, extensive use of blackboard, Elmo, smart board, adobe, foreign language font keyboards/computer software and other language teaching technologies - Evaluated program effectiveness and student performance, provided expertise on military language applications, sourced authentic instructional media and developed testing instruments - Worked w/SMEs to identify what students need to learn, developed objectives and ensured content matched objectives, revised/rewrote content to shape it for learning needs, structured content/activities for student learning, created media to support learning (e.g., visual aids for face-to-face, various multimedia for e-learning and online), developed assessments, adapted materials created for one format to another format (i.e. face-to-face to e-learning)

summary: - Squadron Superintendent responsible for all facets of Formal Training Unit operations, responsible for recruiting and staffing for 4 specialty careers within the organization. - Senior intelligence professional with airborne experience in RIVET JOINT, COMPASS CALL and SILENT SHIELD, ground experience with the Afghanistan Remote Operations Cryptologic Center (AROCC) and leadership duties with Project LIBERTY - Heavy focus on education and training as a Command Language Program Manager, RIVET JOINT instructor and evaluator, SILENT SHIELD Cryptologic Skills Program Manager, COMPASS CALL instructor, ACC course manager, Formal Training Unit Superintendent, Defense Language Institute Military Language Instructor and Superintendent of Language Operations - Cryptologic Language Analyst (SIGINT) w/19+ years of experience in training, administrative support, data base creation & management, scheduling, building and presenting intelligence briefings, overall computer application and maintenance proficiency, maintaining operations budgets, developing, coordinating and implementing operational plans - Tactical and strategic level experience in deployed operations as a leader, operator and mission planner during fourteen deployments – 7 x OSW, 2 x ONW, 2 x OIF, 2 x OEF, 1 x OND

title: Superintendent, Language Analysis Cell
description: - Led 32 military and civilian personnel, trained 4 new hires on Voice Language Analysis, organized schedules and realigned resources to streamline coalition support to 14 partner nations - 24/7 spt to ISAF, bolstered counter insurgency, force protection and village stability ops - Processed 54 high-priority intelligence products, bolstered spt to US Cyber Command 40% - Performed voice language analysis, supervised high value target characterization and pre-strike target verification, provided quality control and analysis for sensitive targets, accomplished 3.4K taskings and produced 2.8K intelligence reports, QC’d intel products prior to customer delivery

summary: - Squadron Superintendent responsible for all facets of Formal Training Unit operations, responsible for recruiting and staffing for 4 specialty careers within the organization. - Senior intelligence professional with airborne experience in RIVET JOINT, COMPASS CALL and SILENT SHIELD, ground experience with the Afghanistan Remote Operations Cryptologic Center (AROCC) and leadership duties with Project LIBERTY - Heavy focus on education and training as a Command Language Program Manager, RIVET JOINT instructor and evaluator, SILENT SHIELD Cryptologic Skills Program Manager, COMPASS CALL instructor, ACC course manager, Formal Training Unit Superintendent, Defense Language Institute Military Language Instructor and Superintendent of Language Operations - Cryptologic Language Analyst (SIGINT) w/19+ years of experience in training, administrative support, data base creation & management, scheduling, building and presenting intelligence briefings, overall computer application and maintenance proficiency, maintaining operations budgets, developing, coordinating and implementing operational plans - Tactical and strategic level experience in deployed operations as a leader, operator and mission planner during fourteen deployments – 7 x OSW, 2 x ONW, 2 x OIF, 2 x OEF, 1 x OND

summary: - Squadron Superintendent responsible for all facets of Formal Training Unit operations, responsible for recruiting and staffing for 4 specialty careers within the organization. - Senior intelligence professional with airborne experience in RIVET JOINT, COMPASS CALL and SILENT SHIELD, ground experience with the Afghanistan Remote Operations Cryptologic Center (AROCC) and leadership duties with Project LIBERTY - Heavy focus on education and training as a Command Language Program Manager, RIVET JOINT instructor and evaluator, SILENT SHIELD Cryptologic Skills Program Manager, COMPASS CALL instructor, ACC course manager, Formal Training Unit Superintendent, Defense Language Institute Military Language Instructor and Superintendent of Language Operations - Cryptologic Language Analyst (SIGINT) w/19+ years of experience in training, administrative support, data base creation & management, scheduling, building and presenting intelligence briefings, overall computer application and maintenance proficiency, maintaining operations budgets, developing, coordinating and implementing operational plans - Tactical and strategic level experience in deployed operations as a leader, operator and mission planner during fourteen deployments – 7 x OSW, 2 x ONW, 2 x OIF, 2 x OEF, 1 x OND

title: Command Language Program Manager
description: - Performed analysis, prepared tech reports, provided intel inputs to national level customers - Persian-Farsi global and cryptologic SME, Staff Persian-Farsi linguist, instructor & flight evaluator, executed initial qualification training, trained & supervised all new linguists - Commander appointed Command Language Program Manager due to outstanding ability and continuous initiative as a Senior Airman (E-4), managed the budget at both the unit and HQ level - Coordinated language training/maintenance for 150+ home-station/geographically separated operating location linguists, coordinated/scheduled/administered global/technical language testing, researched/obtained language training events/materials for language maintenance

title: Senior Watch Officer
description: Managed collection resources for airborne and global response collection conducted against worldwide targets in accordance with DoD tasking. Provided real-time operational management of remote collection sites, equipment, and data forwarding links with the authority to implement ad hoc tasking for up to 72 hours. • Devised a comprehensive program for quarterly SIGINT nuclear weapons support (SNS) training, and administered the training module to all operations center personnel. Impact: The training was instrumental in raising the operations center test scores by 8 points during the next scheduled test. • Developed a working aid to identify, in the primary operations center log shared by all four teams, the originators of a type of formatted tactical report supporting an ongoing military operation. Impact: The project was driven by a request from the chief of the operations center, and provided each team chief with a more comprehensive look at certain critical segments of the military operation. • Instituted a mandatory training program to keep members of my team conversant with reporting and handling procedures for time-sensitive reporting. Impact: The team later achieved the highest score among all four operations center teams.

title: Special Assistant for Crisis Management
description: Served as the focal point for reporting policy and dissemination during crises. Represented the directorate chief at Crisis Management Steering Group and Intelligence Community meetings, and in dealings with the Special Representative to DCI for Intelligence Disclosure. • Developed new procedures for providing extended SIGINT support to the Commanding General of an international peace keeping force. Impact: Such support improved both force protection and strategic planning. • Drafted and implemented innovative guidance which allowed for direct, real-time geolocational support to the government of a U.S. ally during two separate operations to rescue hostages held by an international terrorist group. Impact: The vehicle provided the first tailored reporting for collection site customers.

title: Team Chief, Cryptologic Services Group
description: Supervised military analysts who provided real-time interpretation, advice, and assistance in SIGINT to the NMJIC Deputy Director for Intelligence (DDI) and, ultimately, the J2. The team prepared a daily summary of significant SIGINT products gleaned from NSA and field reporting which was sent to members of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, military services intelligence chiefs, and senior policy makers at the Pentagon. Provided technical guidance on intelligence reporting and classification issues for NMCC analytic desks, and oversaw distribution of SIGINT products to J2 target analysts. • Developed plans to standardize training for incoming team chiefs and the procedure for producing the daily summary of significant SIGINT products. Impact: Allowed the active duty military analysts to work effectively while substituting on different teams (a frequent practice with personal leave and required military training) and ensured the customer a high-quality intelligence summary regardless of the team producing it. • Initiated a new procedure for disseminating to the NMJIC DDI and Deputy Director for Operations, J3, time-sensitive intelligence information from the products of foreign intelligence partners. Impact: Made critical information from Second and Third Parties available to Department of Defense principals on a more-timely basis.

summary: TS/SCI Clearance Full Scope Polygraph Spanish ILR score of 3+/3+/4 B.A. History Career Profile ￼ Eight years of experience in special operations.  Six years experience as a US Army Ranger in the 75th Ranger Regiment analyzing IMINT, HUMINT and SIGINT and integration of ISR to build targeting packages and produce intelligence products to action time sensitive and high value targets in the CJSOTF targeting line of operations (counterinsurgency and counter IED). 3 deployments to OEF and 3 deployments to OIF all in direct support of CJSOTF.  Full knowledge of intelligence cycle, collection management cycle, and geospatial analysis and the integration of ISR to plan and conduct direct action missions, special reconnaissance, and sensitive site exploitation and clandestine insertions . title: US Army Ranger
description: Plan and conduct special operations as a member of the 75th Ranger Regiment as part of CJSOTF.  Analyze HUMINT, IMINT, and SIGINT and integreate ISR into the intelligence cycle to carry out counterterrorism operations against high value targets during three deployments to OIF and three deployments to OEF. summary: Collegiately competed at the University of Wisconsin Whitewater as well as Concordia University now am completing my degree in business/economics at Northeastern Illinois University. I have a passion for the game of basketball and have coached AAU, Travel, and Feeder Teams for the past four years now. Inspiring others to commit to long-term goals physically and academically to prepare them with the necessary tools to succeed in other aspects of life, not just basketball. Compassionate about teaching basketball, as a one-time player and now current coach, stressing the importance of healthy physical and mental habits is key. With a great deal of experience coaching, the awareness of each athlete’s different personality is key, and being seasoned to meet each athletes’ needs mentally and physically as players is crucial to success. One holds an impressive track record of handling and coordinating daily practice schedules, assisting in player skill development, analyzing game film, season game schedules, and conducting community service work.

title: Strategic and Operational Information Operations Planner
description: Mr. Harris is an expert in Information Operations planning execution, policy and doctrine. He brings recent, relevant experience in all core competencies of Information Operations–Information Warfare (IO-IW) as well as Theater Security Cooperation, Intelligence collection, analysis and reporting of SIGINT (ELINT, COMINT) and National Reconnaissance Operations. He is a Certified Navy Instructor, Master Training Specialist and Certified Level 5 Navy IO Planner. Mr. Harris has over Twenty-six years experience in C4ISR, technical intelligence, operations management; including analysis and reporting, combat systems operations, and program management. He has supported Theater Commanders with detailed strategic IO plans, JOPES and Integrated Joint Special Technical Operations (IJSTO). He has relevant recent experience with doctrine, policy and the approval authorities which correspond to the complex methodologies involved with the employment of kinetic and non-kinetic applications. A recognized expert in strategic and operational planning, information operations, and communication strategy; he led numerous operational efforts, and personally authored the commander’s objectives, effects and tasks for operations in the AFRICOM, CENTCOM, PACOM and SOUTHCOM areas of responsibility. Command Civilian of the Year (COY) 2008, as Strategic Information Operations (IO) Planner for the development of real world, exercise and experimental joint IO plans supporting Theater commanders including in depth analysis of Political, Military, Economic, Social, Infrastructure, & Information (PMESII).

title: FLEET TRAINING DEPARTMENT HEAD
description: Led cryptologic and Information Operation (IO) training, command, fleet and Joint assets through 22 formal courses of instruction at the Cryptologic Readiness Group. As Fleet Training Department Head, he directed oversight and management of 38 U.S. Navy and Canadian Instructors providing state of the art waterfront training strategy for cryptologic and Information Warfare (IW) support to fleet operations. Incorporated live training environments with emphasis on team leadership, which yielded the Cryptologic Stimulator Exercise (CSE). Performed ELINT collection to build safe for flight corridor; mitigating SAM threats to coalition aircraft, facilitating “feet dry” sorties supporting all warfare missions. This corridor, still in use today, significantly increased the overall effectiveness of National Reconnaissance Operations. Researched and developed more than 100 ELINT technical working aids for theater operations. Generated effective daily, weekly, and monthly SIGINT coverage and collection management plans throughout an extended deployment for the Harry S. Truman Battle Group. Direct Support Program Manager for over 350 Atlantic Fleet officer and enlisted personnel and the associated deployable equipment augmentation to cryptologic capable ships and aircraft in support of 14 joint operations. Responsible for the validation, endorsement and tasking of Atlantic Fleets Tactical Crypotologic Support (TCS) personnel in support of Navy Special Warfare requirements. Expertly planned and executed a budget in excess of $250K.

title: Command Language Program Manager/Passport Agent
description: Manages the Brigade Command Language Program (CLP) by implementing and maintaining language training programs for subordinate battalions located at different sites in CONUS and PACOM AOR. Uses knowledge of intelligence collection processes and procedures in HUMINT, SIGINT, and Counterintelligence to provide direction for language training programs. Serves as the brigade's technical authority on language training programs and the functional expert for intelligence language related training programs. Develops innovative distance learning programs to leverage technology, computer-assisted instruction and comprehensive teacher training programs. Manages The Army Language Program (TALP/TDLP) and Consolidated Cryptologic Program (CCP) budgets by projecting training needs, submitting budget requests and monitoring expenditures. Develops, coordinates and oversees special projects to include serving as a test site for new equipment and materials, language competition, DLI Train the Trainer workshops, and collaborates with higher headquarters to offer specialized language courses. Performs annual CLP inspections of subordinate units.
